"{\"uid\": \"straitstimes.com-sport-tennis-murray-says-paris-olympics-will-be-final-tournament\", \"text\": \"Choose edition  Search  singapore  asia  world  opinion  life  business  sport  Visual  Podcasts  SPH Rewards  STClassifieds  Paid press releases  Advertise with us  FAQs  Contact us  Sign up now:Get the biggest sports news in your inbox  Andy Murray during practice at Roland Garros on July 22, ahead of the Paris Olympics which will be held at the site of the French Open.  PHOTO: REUTERS  Published\\u00c2Jul 23, 2024, 04:04 PM  Updated\\u00c2Jul 23, 2024, 10:32 PM  PARIS\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0093Two-time Olympic singles champion Andy Murray said on July 23 that the tennis competition at the Paris Games will be the final event of his career.  The 37-year-old, widely regarded as one of Britain\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s all-time great sportsmen, won singles gold in 2012 and 2016, apart from capturing three Grand Slam titles in a glittering career.  \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cArrived in Paris for my last-ever tennis tournament @Olympics,\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d he said on X.  \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cCompeting for Britain has been by far the most memorable weeks of my career and I\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099m extremely proud to get to do it one final time.\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d  Earlier in July, the injury-plagued Murray bade an emotional farewell at Wimbledon \\u00e2\\u0080\\u0093 where he won two Slam titles \\u00e2\\u0080\\u0093 following a doubles defeat partnering his brother Jamie.  The Scot, who underwent surgery on June 22 to remove a spinal cyst which was compressing his nerves and making him lose control and power in his right leg, decided he was not fit enough for the demands of singles competition there.  The Olympic tennis competition begins on July 27 and Murray \\u00e2\\u0080\\u0093 who has struggled over the years since having hip-resurfacing surgery in 2019 \\u00e2\\u0080\\u0093 will be playing both singles and doubles.  Meanwhile, Olympic silver medallist Marketa Vondrousova of the Czech Republic has withdrawn from Paris due to a hand injury, with Poland\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s Hubert Hurkacz pulling out as well.  Vondrousova reached the women\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s final in Tokyo three years ago, losing to Belinda Bencic.  Katerina Siniakova, who won gold at the last Olympics in doubles and is a nine-time Slam champion in women\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s doubles, will replace her in the singles and Linda Noskova will play doubles with Karolina Muchova.  Hurkacz was forced to retire from his Wimbledon second-round match when he dived for a volley but landed badly and injured his knee, and has not recovered in time to compete in Paris.  Other notable absences from the Games include world No. 3 Aryna Sabalenka, Ons Jabeur, Emma Raducanu, Ben Shelton and Tokyo men\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s singles bronze-medal winner Pablo Carreno Busta.  In cycling, Tour de France champion Tadej Pogacar has been ruled out after the three-week race, the Slovenian Olympic Committee said on July 22.  The 25-year-old, who won his third Tour a day earlier,was not selected because of fatigue, the committee said.  He was one of the favourites, alongside Dutchman Mathieu van der Poel, for the Olympic road race on Aug 3.  \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cHe will be replaced by his national team colleague Domen Novak,\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d a statement said.  Defending champion Richard Carapaz, who won the mountains classification at the Tour, was also not selected by Ecuador.REUTERS  Olympics 2024  Olympics  Andy Murray  Retirement  E-paper  Newsletters  Podcasts  RSS Feed  About Us  Terms & Conditions  Personal Data Protection Notice  Need help? Reach us here.  Advertise with us    \"}"